          <p class="text-secondary">
            The bottle measures about 10.5 inches tall with a 3.5-inch base —
            a solid fit for most cup holders and bags. At roughly 600 grams
            (1.6 lbs), it strikes a balance between sturdy construction and
            everyday portability.
          </p>

          <h2>Our use case</h2>
          <p>
            This bottle has become part of our daily routine. Each of us owns
            one and uses it every day. We've moved away from plastic bottles
            and to-go cups almost entirely, sticking mainly to water, and this
            has been our go-to way to stay hydrated. During the summer we load
            it up with ice and water in the morning and still have cold,
            refreshing drinks well into the day.
          </p>
          <p>
            What really stands out is the durability. These bottles have taken
            plenty of abuse — dropped on pavement, bounced across jagged
            volcanic rock, even slipped into rivers like the McKenzie. One was
            briefly lost along the Rogue Gorge and still came back in solid
            shape. Even after all that, the exterior coating has held up with
            only minor cosmetic wear.
          </p>
          <p>
            The chug cap is convenient and easy to use, though it's not
            perfect. Because it's made of plastic, repeated drops and carrying
            it by the handle over time can wear down the threads slightly,
            which may lead to occasional leaks. It's something to keep an eye
            on — having a backup cap on hand is a smart move if you're using
            it heavily outdoors.
          </p>

